         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Melbourne bot. &amp; zool. ¶  ¶ Garden ¶ 5. Nov. 1860 ¶ Sir ¶  ¶ I have the honor of submitting for your favorable consideration the byefollowing communication from Ch. Ledger Esq of Arthursleigh, New Sou...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">60.11.05b</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To William Nicholson</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">P60/10117, unit 748, VPRS 1189/P inward registered correspondence, VA 475 Chief Secretary's Department, Public Record Office, Victoria.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; "/>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn0" n="1">
                  <p rend="FootnoteText"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The file cover says Ledger's<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>letter was 'containing a proposition for the introduction of an addl number of Alpacas'.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>See also M to W. Nicholson, 3 November 1860.</p>
               </note>Melbourne bot. &amp; zool.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Garden</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">5. Nov. 1860</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Sir</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have the honor of submitting for your favorable consideration the byefollowing communication from Ch. Ledger Esq of Arthursleigh, New South Wales.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn1" n="2">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>C. Ledger to M, 1 November 1860<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-weight: bold; ">this another letter - check again at PRO</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                     </p>
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="color: #C00000; ">NB: the version printed in the Age, 3 November , p. 6, see<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <ref target="https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/154885484?">
                           <seg rend="Hyperlink" style="color: #0563C1; ">here</seg>
                        </ref>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="color: #C00000; ">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>is dated 30 October.</seg>
                     </p>
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; margin-left: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="color: #C00000; ">The one in the Argus see<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <ref target="https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/5692690">
                           <seg rend="Hyperlink" style="color: #0563C1; ">here</seg>
                        </ref>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="color: #C00000; ">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>is also dated 30 October, at the end of the letter, and M's covering letter is dated 1 November. <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>What date is actually on the copy from VPRO??</seg>
                     </p>
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; margin-left: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="color: #C00000; ">M may indeed have sent it twice, as there are differences beween this and<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-weight: bold; color: #C00000; ">60-11-03 with the <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="color: #C00000; ">location as<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">Q60/10079, unit 748, VPRS 1189/P,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="color: #C00000; ">suggesting that for some reason M sent a copy of Ledgers' report to two different officials, each reporting to Nicholson? But it is very odd indeed, unless there were two different documents from Ledger. We have 60-11-01as not with this letter, but with<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">Q60/10079, unit 748, VPRS 1189/P.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="color: #C00000; ">Was there a differnt report with this one? Ledger had had a meeting with the Chief<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="color: #C00000; ">S</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="color: #C00000; ">ecretary on 2 November, so there is a distinct possibility that he sent a f</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="color: #C00000; ">o</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="color: #C00000; ">llow up report, but I can find no reference to such</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="color: #C00000; ">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>a report in the press. However, I wonder whether it was the one on coca leaves 60-07-05 that might have arisen in the meeting. A bit far fetched, but it is a straw, a second straw coming fom the failure to mention alpacas in this letter, whereas it is explicit in 60-11-03.</seg>
                     </p>
                     <p rend="Normal"
                        style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; color: #C00000; "
                        xml:lang="en">Thoughts overnight:<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     </p>
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; margin-left: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="color: #C00000; ">Since there is no direct evidence that this letter was about alpacas, and 60-11-03 is certainly about that, we link the alpaca report correctly to the earlier letter, and say on this one 'enclosure not found'.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">I have the honor to be,</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Sir,</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>your most obedient servant</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. Mueller.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">The honorable<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">the Chief Secretary<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn2" n="3">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>On 27 June 1863 the Under Secretary, W. Odgers noted that M's letter had been: 'Recd from Mr Moore on Mr O'S retirement'. The 'Mr Moore' was presumably the former Under Secretary, J. Moore; 'Mr O'S' is J.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>O'Shanassy, who had resigned as Chief Secretary on 27 June 1863, after having three discrete terms as Chief Secretary.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
         </div>
      </body>
